INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (441, 2, '2010-09-15 04:05:44', '2010-09-15 11:05:44', '<img class="alignright size-thumbnail wp-image-439" title="CranberrySauce" src="http://www.cookingandmore.com/wp-content/uploads/2010/04/CranberrySauce-150x150.jpg" alt="CranberrySauce" width="150" height="150" />\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">Dear Friends,</p>\r\n\r\nFall weather has not hit in the southwest yet but with Sukkot coming up celebrating the fall harvest and September half gone I feel like the pumpkins and hay bales will soon be decorating everyone\'s front porch.\r\n\r\nKids are back in school, meal time is frenzied,  and working your schedule around after school sports and dance lessons makes you crazed. On top of that, there is all this new bounty from the earth filling the bins at your local supermarket calling to you to be experimented  with at your next meal.\r\n\r\nTry new ingredients;  bake familiar vegetables lightly seasoned and coated with a little olive oil instead of cooking them in boiling salted water.  Cook unpeeled apple slices in 1/2 inch water with just a cinnamon stick and in 15 minutes you can run the apples through a food mill or remove the skins by hand and you will have the most delicious unsweetened apple sauce that  is slightly pink, very nutritious and delicious!  Be creative and explore new foods.\r\n\r\n<strong></strong>\r\n\r\nNot enough recipes here to satisfy you?  Don\'t own a copy of  my book      <em><strong>Entree to Judaism </strong></em>yet<em><strong>?  <em><strong> </strong></em>(Barnes and Noble, Neiman\'s and  your temple gift shop should have it) </strong></em>Can\'t wait for your <em>Reform Judaism Magazine</em> to arrive?  Check out my weekly postings on   <a href="http://www.facebook.com/home.php?ref=home#!/tinawasserman?ref=ts" target="_blank">Facebook </a> and, look for periodic videos on You Tube that I have made to highlight a cooking technique or recipe.\r\n\r\nAnd last, but not least, I am beginning to travel again to give presentations and have book signings so check out my schedule below and if I am in your area, come and say hello...you can even bring your cooking questions with you!\r\n\r\nEat in Good Health!\r\n\r\nTina\r\n\r\nThe following is my September/October schedule\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><strong>September 1: online,</strong> URJ webinar-Rosh Hashanah foods</li>\r\n	<li><strong>September 1: Plano, TX,</strong> Anshai Torah Sisterhood, Neiman\'s Willow Bend 7-9</li>\r\n	<li><strong>September 30: Gladwynne, PA</strong>, Main Line Reform Sisterhood</li>\r\n	<li><strong>October 1: King of Prussia, PA, </strong>Book signing Neiman Marcus 2-4</li>\r\n	<li><strong>October 2: Philadelphia, PA, </strong>Book signing Barnes and Noble Rittenhouse Square 2-4</li>\r\n	<li><strong>October 5: Bryn Mawr, PA, </strong>Teaching, Barrack Academy</li>\r\n	<li><strong>October 16: Dallas, TX,</strong> Talk, WRJ Southwest District Convention</li>\r\n	<li><strong>October 17:  San Rafael, CA</strong>, Talk, Osher Marin JCC Book Fair</li>\r\n	<li><strong>October 19: Palo Alto, CA</strong>, Talk, Peninsula Volunteers Little House Activity Center</li>\r\n	<li><strong>October 20: Albuquerque, NM,</strong> talk Albuquerque JCC Book Fair</li>\r\n	<li><strong>October 24: Glendale, CA</strong>, Talk Temple Sinai</li>\r\n	<li><strong>October 27: Dallas, TX</strong>, Talk, Sisterhood Temple Shalom</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<strong> </strong>\r\n\r\nIf I\'m not coming to you then <a href="http://podcastdownload.npr.org/anon.npr-podcasts/podcast/77/510036/121221265/KERA_121221265.mp3?_kip_ipx=1078152060-1260833421" target="_blank">listen to my appearance on local NPR station KERA</a> to hear me talk about the history and stories in <strong>Entre\'e to Judaism.</strong>', 'Welcome to Tina\'s Kitchen', 0, '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '209-revision-36', '', '', '2010-09-15 04:05:44', '2010-09-15 11:05:44', '', 209, 'http://www.cookingandmore.com/4/209-revision-36', 0, 'revision', '', 0); 
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (443, 1, '2010-11-08 16:57:28', '2010-11-08 23:57:28', '<img class="alignright size-full wp-image-446" title="Newsletter_10Aug1_photoA3" src="http://www.cookingandmore.com/wp-content/uploads/2010/11/Newsletter_10Aug1_photoA3.jpg" alt="" width="200" height="200" />Here is a perfect example of the migration of Jewish cooking.  I created  this taco to incorporate all the flavors of the Southwest United States  while adhering to the tenets of Kashrut.\r\n\r\n<p class="recipehdr">Ingredients</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li> 1 pound fish fillets, skin removed (salmon, sea bass, halibut, or black cod)</li>\r\n	<li>1/4-cup soy sauce</li>\r\n	<li>1 Tablespoon light brown sugar</li>\r\n	<li>6 ounces regular (not lite) beer</li>\r\n	<li>2 large cloves garlic finely minced</li>\r\n	<li>1 cup pecans, coarsely chopped</li>\r\n	<li>2 Tablespoons flour</li>\r\n	<li>1/4 teaspoon salt</li>\r\n	<li>Freshly ground black pepper to taste</li>\r\n	<li>2 Tablespoons extra virgin olive oil</li>\r\n	<li>1 Tablespoon unsalted butter</li>\r\n	<li>4-6 flour tortillas</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p class="recipehdr">Preparation Instructions</p>\r\n\r\n1.	Cut the fish into 1- inch thick strips.\r\n\r\n2.	Combine the soy sauce, brown sugar, beer and minced garlic in a Pyrex  loaf pan or small casserole.  Add the fish and marinate for no more  than 1 hour.\r\n\r\n3.	Combine the chopped pecans, flour, salt and pepper on a plate.	Firmly  press all sides of the fish into the pecan mixture to coat well.\r\n\r\n4.	Preheat the oven to 400F.\r\n\r\n5.	Heat a cast iron skillet over high heat 20 seconds.  Add the olive  oil and butter and heat until the butter is melted and bubbling.\r\n\r\n6.	Reduce the heat to medium high if the mixture begins to smoke, and  add the fish fillets to the pan.  Cook on one side for 1-2 minutes until  nuts are golden brown.\r\n\r\n7.	Flip fish over and then place the entire frying pan in the oven and  bake for 5 minutes more or until fish is firm but still springy.\r\n\r\n8.	Cut the fish pieces in half, if desired and then serve on a flour  tortilla with some pineapple salsa and Ancho chili --Margarita  mayonnaise.\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\nPINEAPPLE MINT SALSA\r\n\r\n1/2 ripe pineapple, peeled cored and cut into small dice\r\n1/2 jalapeno pepper, seeds and inner ribs removed, finely diced\r\n1/3 cup finely diced red onion\r\n1 Tablespoon finely minced Mexican Mint Marigold (or Tarragon)\r\n1 Tablespoon finely minced fresh Mint\r\nJuice of half a lime\r\nPinch of sugar (optional if pineapple isn\'t sweet)\r\n\r\n1.  Combine all of the ingredients in a small serving bowl and refrigerate until needed.\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\nANCHO CHILI, MARGARITA MAYONNAISE\r\n\r\n1/4 cup Hellmann\'s mayonnaise\r\n1 teaspoon Tequila\r\n1/2 teaspoon Grand Marnier or Triple Sec\r\nFresh lime juice to taste\r\n1/8 -1/4 teaspoon McCormick Ancho chili powder\r\n\r\n1.	Whisk the mayonnaise in a small bowl until smooth and then add the remaining ingredients and stir to combine.', 'Pecan Crusted Fish Tacos', 0, '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'pecan-crusted-fish-tacos', '', '', '2010-11-08 17:17:16', '2010-11-09 00:17:16', '', 0, 'http://www.cookingandmore.com/?p=443', 0, 'post', '', 0); 
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (444, 1, '2010-11-08 16:57:17', '2010-11-08 23:57:17', 'Here is a perfect example of the migration of Jewish cooking.  I created  this taco to incorporate all the flavors of the Southwest United States  while adhering to the tenets of Kashrut.\n\nIngredients\n<ul>\n	<li> 1 pound fish fillets, skin removed (salmon, sea bass, halibut, or black cod)</li>\n	<li>1/4-cup soy sauce</li>\n	<li>1 Tablespoon light brown sugar</li>\n	<li>6 ounces regular (not lite) beer</li>\n	<li>2 large cloves garlic finely minced</li>\n	<li>1 cup pecans, coarsely chopped</li>\n	<li>2 Tablespoons flour</li>\n	<li>1/4 teaspoon salt</li>\n	<li>Freshly ground black pepper to taste</li>\n	<li>2 Tablespoons extra virgin olive oil</li>\n	<li>1 Tablespoon unsalted butter</li>\n	<li>4-6 flour tortillas</li>\n</ul>\n<hr />Preparation Instructions\n\n1.	Cut the fish into 1- inch thick strips.\n\n2.	Combine the soy sauce, brown sugar, beer and minced garlic in a Pyrex  loaf pan or small casserole.  Add the fish and marinate for no more  than 1 hour.\n\n3.	Combine the chopped pecans, flour, salt and pepper on a plate.	Firmly  press all sides of the fish into the pecan mixture to coat well.\n\n4.	Preheat the oven to 400F.\n\n5.	Heat a cast iron skillet over high heat 20 seconds.  Add the olive  oil and butter and heat until the butter is melted and bubbling.\n\n6.	Reduce the heat to medium high if the mixture begins to smoke, and  add the fish fillets to the pan.  Cook on one side for 1-2 minutes until  nuts are golden brown.\n\n7.	Flip fish over and then place the entire frying pan in the oven and  bake for 5 minutes more or until fish is firm but still springy.\n\n8.	Cut the fish pieces in half, if desired and then serve on a flour  tortilla with some pineapple salsa and Ancho chili --Margarita  mayonnaise.\n\n\n\n\nPINEAPPLE MINT SALSA\n1/2 ripe pineapple, peeled cored and cut into small dice\n1/2 jalapeno pepper, seeds and inner ribs removed, finely diced\n1/3 cup finely diced red onion\n1 Tablespoon finely minced Mexican Mint Marigold (or Tarragon)\n1 Tablespoon finely minced fresh Mint\nJuice of half a lime\nPinch of sugar (optional if pineapple isn\'t sweet)\n----------------------------------------------------------------------------\n1.  Combine all of the ingredients in a small serving bowl and refrigerate until needed.\n\n\nANCHO CHILI, MARGARITA MAYONNAISE\n\n1/4 cup Hellmann\'s mayonnaise\n1 teaspoon Tequila\n1/2 teaspoon Grand Marnier or Triple Sec\nFresh lime juice to taste\n1/8 -1/4 teaspoon McCormick Ancho chili powder\n-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------\n1.	Whisk the mayonnaise in a small bowl until smooth and then add the remaining ingredients and stir to combine.', 'Pecan Crusted Fish Tacos', 0, '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '443-revision', '', '', '2010-11-08 16:57:17', '2010-11-08 23:57:17', '', 443, 'http://www.cookingandmore.com/443-revision', 0, 'revision', '', 0); 
